						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Odds-stacked-against-San-harvesters-of-devil-s-claw" title="Odds stacked against San harvesters of devil’s claw" alt="link">Odds stacked against San harvesters of devil’s claw</a></h2>

	
					<p>Devil’s claw – scientific name Harpagophytum zeyheri, or Xam!abo to the Khwe, a tribe of the San people and original inhabitants of what is today Bwabwata National Park in northeast Namibia – is a natural remedy for arthritis. Picked up by the pharmaceutical industry in the 1960s, devil’s claw was sold overseas, but no one in the community made a fortune from it. ‘The trade was unregulated and unsustainable’, recalls Friedrich Alpers from Integrated Resource Development and Nature Conservation (IRDNC). (Source: IPS, 8 May 2010)</p>
							<p><span class="date">31/05/2010</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Odds-stacked-against-San-harvesters-of-devil-s-claw">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
